---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import loginTrace from "../cookbooks/tdd-login-form.yaml?raw";
import searchTrace from "../cookbooks/tdd-search-filter.yaml?raw";
---
<Base title="MCP Trace Examples & Cookbooks">
  <h1>MCP Trace Examples & Agent Cookbooks</h1>
  <p class="muted">
    Reproducible <code>.yaml</code> traces showing how a coding agent can
    drive a running React Native dev app via brna's MCP server. Each
    trace is replayable with <code>brna trace replay &lt;file&gt;</code>
    and serves both as documentation and as a regression fixture.
  </p>

  <h2>What's in a trace</h2>
  <p>
    A trace is a YAML document with two sections: <code>metadata</code>
    (session id, start/stop timestamps) and <code>events</code> (an
    ordered list of <code>snap</code> and <code>act</code> entries).
    Each event carries the snapshots it observed and, for actions, the
    <code>SnapshotDiff</code> that was produced. Targeted actions —
    <code>brna act tap "#submit"</code> — automatically focus that diff
    on the action's target so the trace stays narrow even when the rest
    of the screen ticks (clocks, polling banners, animations).
  </p>

  <section>
    <h2>Cookbook 1 — Validating a login form</h2>
    <p>
      The agent expects the empty login form to surface an inline error.
      It taps <code>#submit</code>, watches a global toast appear in the
      diff, then re-snapshots with <code>--target #submit</code> to
      confirm the toast persists. Notice how the toast — an overlay —
      is preserved by <code>filterDiffByTarget</code> even though it
      lives outside the target's subtree.
    </p>
    <pre><code>{loginTrace}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Cookbook 2 — Filtering a list as the user types</h2>
    <p>
      The agent types <code>react</code> into a search box and verifies
      the list narrows to one row. The header clock keeps ticking
      every second, but <code>--target "#list"</code> keeps that noise
      out of the recorded diff so the agent can focus on the assertion
      that matters.
    </p>
    <pre><code>{searchTrace}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <h2>Replaying a trace</h2>
  <pre><code>brna trace replay ./tdd-login-form.yaml</code></pre>
  <p>
    Replay re-runs each <code>act</code> against the live runtime and
    asserts that the recorded snapshots still match. Mismatches exit
    with code 6 and a path to the diverging event — perfect for CI
    smoke tests or for catching regressions during a refactor.
  </p>
</Base>
